title: For Sale:  Heavily Modified Mosin Nagant
postcontent: I have for sale a very heavily modified Mosin Nagant.  I bought the rifle as a standard Russian made 91/30.  The rifle was made in 1940 and still had the cosmoline on it when I bought it.  Everything on this rifle has been changed out or modified.  The only factory parts left on it are the barrel and receiver.  Starting out front: the barrel was cut back to about 24in and threaded 5/8x24 and a radial style muzzle brake was installed.  This muzzle brake makes it feel like you are shooting a 243.  The receiver has an ATI scope mount installed and bolt itself has an ATI bent bolt handle installed.  The receiver and barrel have a camo paint job on them I did myself.  The original wood stock was replaced with an Archangel stock, this stock has a fully adjustable length-of-pull and an adjustable cheek rest.  The rifle has a Timney trigger installed that is set a 3 pounds and it has a thumb safety.  A 2in section of picatinny rail was installed on the forend of the stock and it has a 6-9in bipod attached to it.  The rifle has a Primary Arms 4-16x44 illuminated mil dot scope mounted with a set of Warne Permanent Attach 30mm scope rings.  I have only put about 60 rounds through this rifle, it is not even broken in yet but this rifle shoots pretty well with surplus ammo and it will shoot 1 moa with decent factory ammo.  I have around 500 rounds of surplus ammo that is included with the rifle.  Most of it is from a 440rd spam can of standard 147 grain full metal jacket.  There is about 100 rounds of 147 grain silver tip which is the armor piercing steel core round.  I am asking $500 for the rifle with all of the ammo.  Everything listed is included with the rifle.  I have over $900 invested, feel free to look up the prices and reviews for yourself.  I did not put junk on this rifle.The best to contact me is through text REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Kahles Helia L 3-12x56mm FFP Scope w/ #7 (Duplex) Reticle
postcontent: This is a nice example of the Helia L series scope by Kahles.  The scope is made in Austria, and is every bit the equal to Schmidt & Bender, Swarovski and Zeiss which are also made in Europe.  The same scope will cost you $2,600 today.  It's the 3-12x56mm version which is suberb in low-light conditions.  The #7 reticle is what we in the U.S. call a duplex reticle.  The reticle is in the First Focal Plane (FFP) which means the reticle gets larger as the magnification increases.  This feature is in all the fine scopes and allows you to still see the reticle clearly at high magnification.  The scope is matte finish and has a few marks.  There is some slight wear around the leading edge of the front objective.  And there are a couple of scratches on the ocular, but they are pretty much underneath the scope label, which will be facing down when mounted on your rifle.  Otherwise the scope is in pretty good shape.  No ring marks.  The glass is also in good shape.  The scope shows a little wear here and there, but overall is in nice shape.  I'm happy to ship it anywhere.  Payment by cash or USPS money order.  I will also accept Paypal id you pay the 3% fee.  I have a lot of photos of the scope, taken outside in natural light, and will be happy to send them to you.  If you need an integrity check on me, just check out my Ebay feedback for Scottielover1.

title: Want To Buy:  WTB:   Husqvarna 1900 long action or rifle
postcontent: Want to Buy:  Husqvarna 1900 long action or rifle (Doesn't matter if it has barrel and/or stock).The 1900 Action rifles was made by Husqvarna from 1967 to 1972, then by Carl Gustav from 1972 to 1979.  The 8000 and 9000 variants are also considered 1900 actions I believe.  Might be labeled "model 1970" or any number of other labels (including the phrases 1900, 8000, 9000, HVA, Husqvarna, FFV, CG) - but I think you know whether you have a 1900 action or not.This is the later push feed with sleek modern bolt shroud, not the earlier 1600 or 1640 action based on the controlled feed small ring Mauser.I will pay a finders fee of $25 (mail you a money order) if you find one for me that I end up getting.  I'm going to make a 6.5x55 out of this one.  Keep in mind that many of the 1900 chambered for short action rounds are actually built on the long action which I need, so .243s, .308s, etc. will work.Thanks a lot.  Text or call REDACTED.

title: For Sale:  Custom Long Range Precision Varmint/Target Rifle- Ruger .204
postcontent: This listing is for a lightly used precision rifle in Ruger .204. This is a very unique weapon and I pretty much built it from the ground up. The rifle is based on a single shot heavy Savage competition target action. The trigger is a savage target trigger tunable down to about 1/2 pound. It has an HS Precision stock with a custom rubber like paint job in olive drab with black web. Photo taken before paint job.The barrel is a custom 24 inch McGowen full bull barrel with a 1 in 11 twist to stabelize 40 grain .204 rounds. Muzzle has a flat recessed crown. Built into the foregrip, under the barrel, is a custom barrel tuning device which is adjustable by turning a screw head built into the end of the fore grip. The concept is the exact opposite of reloading. Every gun and barrel has a unique set of vibrational characteristics. Reloading allows the shooter to fine tune the round around the gun for best accuracy. This barrel tuner allows you to pick your preferred ammo and fine tune the barrel around that ammo. It took me one afternoon and a couple boxes of ammo to tune the barrel.The optics is a Bushnell elite DOA rifle scope 6500 4.5-30 x 50mm with a 30mm tube held in place with Burris signiture zee rings.The rifle has a nice Harris bipod and hard carry case.The rifle has about 200 rounds through it and I don't know of anything wrong with it. I have developed a severe carpel tunnel condition and my shooting days are over, except for maybe a pistol in a real life self defense situation. But no more recreational shooting.I have included a picture of my best 3-round group shot at 100 yards off the bipod, with the barrel tuned and under near perfect conditions, except for about a 2-3 knot left to right breaze. That's a 1/8" group. one ragged hole. That was my best group but I rutinely shot 1/4-3/8" every time at the range.If you were to build this gun yourself, it would cost about $2,500 with competitively priced parts. Local transfer only. No trades or shipping please.Thanks for looking,
